{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583545"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:18:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:18:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11674"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11674"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.36,0.44,0.05,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4295"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51259"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4295"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11674"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36540"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1307"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"9866"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5791"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6419"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9812"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14027"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16926"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18428"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31619"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51259","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51259"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with dyspnoea when lying down at night, as well as swelling of his feet. He has coughed up frothy sputum and gained 4 kg of weight in the past week. He has a history of chronic alcoholism, high cholesterol, and decompensated heart failure. He is prescribed furosemide for presumed acute pulmonary oedema.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Through which of the following physiological processes does furosemide achieve its clinical benefit in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti-diuretic hormone","Renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system","Frank-Starling mechanism","Atrial natriuretic peptide","Sympathetic nervous system activation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s clinical features are consistent with decompensated heart failure. Furosemide is a loop diuretic that works by inhibiting the sodium-potassium-chloride cotransporter in the thick ascending limb of the loop of Henle. This results in increased excretion of sodium, chloride, and water, thereby reducing fluid overload and improving symptoms of heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EFrank-Starling mechanism\u003C/strong\u003E is an intrinsic autoregulatory mechanism in the heart. It describes the relationship between cardiac stretch (or preload), contractility and stroke volume. Under normal circumstances, an increase in ventricular filling results in increased contractility, allowing the heart to pump all the blood returned to it. However, too much stretch (such as in decompensated heart failure) leads to decreased contractility and pulmonary congestion. Furosemide corrects this by causing a reduction in fluid and therefore preload, allowing for optimisation of cardiac output via the Frank-Starling mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-diuretic hormone (ADH)\u003C/strong\u003E secretion results in water reabsorption at the distal convoluted tubule of the kidney. Furosemide has no direct effect on ADH levels or function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Erenin-angiotensin-aldosterone system (RAAS)\u003C/strong\u003E is activated when there is a low glomerular filtration rate (GFR) and has the net result of increasing water and sodium absorption in the kidney to increase circulating volume. This system can be detrimentally activated in heart failure with decreased cardiac output as a result of renal hypoperfusion, which can worsen symptoms. Antagonism of RAAS is therefore indicated in heart failure with reduced ejection fraction and is achieved with ACE inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial natriuretic peptide (ANP)\u003C/strong\u003E is released by the atrial cells in response to stretch, which can occur when there is more fluid in the body. The action of ANP is to inhibit sodium and water reabsorption, which would be helpful in decompensated heart failure. However, furosemide does not have a direct effect on ANP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESympathetic nervous system activation\u003C/strong\u003E is an innate compensatory mechanism of the heart to increase heart rate and contractility. Whilst this is useful in the short term, the persistent sympathetic activation seen in heart failure can have negative long-term consequences. Therefore, antagonism of sympathetic drive in certain categories of heart failure has been shown to lead to improved morbidity and mortality. The drug class used for this is a beta blocker.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Furosemide works by reducing fluid in the body and optimising preload and therefore cardiac output via the Frank-Starling mechanism in decompensated heart failure."],"references":["Jacob R, Dierberger B, Kissling G. Functional significance of the Frank-Starling mechanism under physiological and pathophysiological conditions. European Heart Journal. 1992;13(suppl E):7-14. Available at: https://academic.oup.com/eurheartj/article-abstract/13/suppl_E/7/486060"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36540"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11674"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36540"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-23T11:04:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-23T11:05:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4295"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51259"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"40","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/40"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGr